  "Taking the absolute difference of components": "",
  "Adding the magnitudes and subtracting the directions": "",
  "Vector subtraction u - v is defined as adding u to the negative of v: u - v = u + (-v). In component form, <a1-a2, b1-b2>. Geometrically, u - v points from the tip of v to the tip of u when both start at the same point.": "",
  "What is the commutative property of vector addition?": "",
  "u + v = u - v always": "",
  "u + v = v + u (order does not matter)": "",
  "u + 0 = u": "",
  "(u + v) + w = u + (v + w)": "",
  "The commutative property states that u + v = v + u for all vectors u and v. The order of addition does not affect the result. This is shown geometrically by the parallelogram law.": "",
  "What does it mean for a set of vectors to be linearly independent?": "",
  "All vectors have the same magnitude": "",
  "The vectors all point in the same direction": "",
  "No vector in the set can be written as a linear combination of the others": "",
  "All vectors are perpendicular to each other": "",
  "Vectors are linearly independent if no vector can be expressed as a linear combination of the others, or equivalently, the only solution to c1*v1 + c2*v2 + ... = 0 is c1 = c2 = ... = 0. In 2D, two non-parallel vectors are linearly independent.": "",
  "What is the associative property of vector addition?": "",
  "u + 0 = u, particularly regarding adding": "",
  "c(u + v) = cu + cv when evaluated systematically": "",
  "(u + v) + w = u + (v + w) (grouping does not matter)": "",
  "u + v = v + u, particularly regarding": "",
  "The associative property states that (u + v) + w = u + (v + w). When adding three or more vectors, the grouping (which two you add first) does not change the final result.": "",
